                    "Text": "=== Operation 1 Result (Text) ===\n---\ncreated: 2026-05-06T20:13:38.306Z\nupdated: 2026-05-06T20:13:38.306Z\n---\n\n# SignalArk MCP Server — Product & Technical Plan\n\n---\n\n## Decision & Status\n\n**Status: APPROVED — Build after launch stabilization / internal beta first.**\n\nMCP is approved directionally as a strategic differentiator but is not more urgent than making the core product reliable and easy to understand. Do not let MCP distract from launch readiness.\n\n### Prerequisites before MCP build\n- Production stability hardening\n- Dashboard/feed simplification  \n- Onboarding first-value reliability\n- Signal quality stabilization\n- Content-to-pipeline dogfooding\n\n### Refined V1 scope\n\n**V1a — Read-only only (build first):**\n- `search_signals`\n- `get_signal_detail`\n- `get_top_moving_accounts`\n- `get_account_timeline`\n- `explain_account_priority`\n- `get_content_opportunities`\n\n**V1b — Draft tools (build after V1a validated):**\n- `generate_outreach_draft`\n- `generate_linkedin_draft`\n\nNo write tools in V1.\n\n### Do NOT expose until underlying product areas are stable\n- Social Signals lead classification\n- LinkedIn comments/reactions beta\n- Use-case classification if still changing\n- Source Router validation tools\n- Provider-heavy scanning tools\n\n### Core MCP principles (non-negotiable)\n- Read-heavy first\n- Workspace-scoped only\n- No workspaceId accepted from tool input\n- No auto-send\n- No autonomous outbound\n- No CRM mutation without explicit confirmation\n- No raw provider payloads\n- No beta data unless enabled\n- Evidence and caveats included in every response\n- Audit logging for every tool call\n- Credit metering for draft tools\n\n---\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nSignalArk should build an MCP (Model Context Protocol) server to position itself as a **Signal OS for AI assistants**. MCP is the emerging open standard that Claude, ChatGPT, Cursor, and other AI clients use to connect to external tools. By exposing SignalArk's unique intelligence layer — buyer signals, account timelines, social engagement, competitive displacement, champion movement, content opportunities, and evidence-backed why-now context — through MCP, users gain the ability to reason over their entire signal graph conversationally.\n\n**What it unlocks:**\n- Users ask \"Which accounts should I focus on today?\" and get prioritized, evidence-backed answers sourced from their own signal data\n- AI clients can chain SignalArk tools together: search signals → explain account priority → draft outreach — all grounded in real evidence\n- SignalArk becomes the intelligence substrate for any AI workflow, not just its own UI\n- Competitive moat: no other GTM signal platform offers MCP access. First-mover advantage in the \"AI-native GTM\" category\n- Retention driver: once users wire SignalArk into their AI workflow, switching cost increases dramatically\n\n**What it is NOT:**\n- Not a generic agent marketplace\n- Not autonomous outbound\n- Not uncontrolled automation\n- Not a replacement for the SignalArk UI — it's a complementary intelligence interface\n\n---\n\n## 2. Product Use Cases\n\n### A. Account Prioritization\n**User asks:** \"Which accounts should I focus on today?\" / \"Why is Acme Corp moving now?\"\n\n**Tool chain:** `get_top_moving_accounts` → `explain_account_priority` → `get_account_next_actions`\n\n**Value:** Replaces the daily ritual of scanning dashboards. The AI client synthesizes signal density, ICP fit, recency, and play matches into a concise briefing. Evidence URLs and signal IDs are included so the user can verify.\n\n### B. Competitive Displacement\n**User asks:** \"Find competitor displacement opportunities this week\" / \"Which accounts are showing pain with [Competitor]?\"\n\n**Tool chain:** `search_signals(category=competitor_dissatisfaction)` → `get_account_timeline` → `generate_outreach_draft`\n\n**Value:** Surfaces breach events, layoff signals, pricing complaints, and support instability that create switching windows. The AI client can cross-reference with the user's account list and ICP fit.\n\n### C. Content-to-Pipeline\n**User asks:** \"Create 3 LinkedIn content ideas from this week's strongest signals\" / \"What's performing well?\"\n\n**Tool chain:** `get_content_opportunities` → `generate_content_angles` → `generate_linkedin_draft` → `get_content_performance`\n\n**Value:** Connects signal intelligence to content creation. Every content idea is grounded in a real market signal, not generic thought leadership. The AI client can iterate on drafts with the user.\n\n### D. Social Intelligence\n**User asks:** \"Who engaged with our latest content?\" / \"Show me ICP-fit engagers\" / \"What conversations matter?\"\n\n**Tool chain:** `get_social_activity` → `get_content_engagers` → `generate_outreach_draft`\n\n**Value:** Surfaces warm leads from social engagement without requiring the user to manually check the Social Signals page. The AI client can filter by ICP fit and warmth score.\n\n### E. Weekly Planning\n**User asks:** \"Plan my week from recent signals\" / \"Summarize what happened since Monday\"\n\n**Tool chain:** `get_recent_high_priority_signals` → `get_top_moving_accounts` → `recommend_play` → `get_account_next_actions`\n\n**Value:** Compound workflow that chains multiple tools into a weekly action plan. The AI client builds a prioritized task list grounded in real signal data.\n\n---\n\n## 3. MCP Tool Groups\n\n### Signals (4 tools)\n\n| Tool | Description | Permission | Credit Cost |\n|------|-------------|------------|-------------|\n| `search_signals` | Search market radar signals by keyword, category, date range, wedge type, confidence threshold. Returns paginated results with per-company limiting. | read | 0 |\n| `get_signal_detail` | Get full detail for a single signal by ID including score explanation, action history, source URLs. | read | 0 |\n| `get_recent_high_priority_signals` | Get top N signals from the last N days, sorted by intent score × confidence. Convenience wrapper over search_signals with smart defaults. | read | 0 |\n| `classify_signal_use_case` | Given a signal ID, return which use cases it's relevant to (displacement, hiring, funding, content, outreach). Rule-based, no LLM. | read | 0 |\n\n**Maps to:** `endpoints/market-radar/signals_GET`, `endpoints/market-radar/detail_GET`, `endpoints/signals/detail_GET`\n\n### Accounts (4 tools)\n\n| Tool | Description | Permission | Credit Cost |\n|------|-------------|------------|-------------|\n| `get_top_moving_accounts` | Returns accounts ranked by recent signal activity, ICP fit, and composite score. Supports filtering by industry, employee range, ICP tier. | read | 0 |\n| `get_account_timeline` | Unified chronological timeline for an account: signals + market radar + social engagement events. Includes source diversity summary. | read | 0 |\n| `explain_account_priority` | For a given account, returns structured explanation: ICP fit score, signal count by family, active plays, deal status, enrichment completeness, recommended persona. | read | 0 |\n| `get_account_next_actions` | Returns the next best actions for an account (existing NBA engine output). Includes action type, priority, reasoning, and action data. | read | 0 |\n\n**Maps to:** `endpoints/accounts/list_GET`, `endpoints/accounts/detail_GET`, `endpoints/accounts/timeline_GET`, `endpoints/ai/next-best-actions_POST` (read from `next_best_actions` table or generate fresh)\n\n### Social (4 tools)\n\n| Tool | Description | Permission | Credit Cost |\n|------|-------------|------------|-------------|\n| `get_social_activity` | Returns recent social engagement events. Filterable by platform, engagement type, warmth score, ICP match tier. | read | 0 |\n| `get_content_engagers` | Returns engagers for a specific published content draft or across all published content. Filterable by ICP fit and warmth. | read | 0 |\n| `get_competitor_social_mentions` | Searches social engagement events and signals for competitor-related mentions. | read | 0 |\n| `get_community_engagement_opportunities` | Returns high-warmth social engagement events that are not yet leads but show engagement potential. | read | 0 |\n\n**Maps to:** `endpoints/social-monitor/posts_GET`, `endpoints/content/engagers/list_GET`, `endpoints/social-monitor/leads_GET`, `endpoints/social-monitor/dashboard_GET`\n\n### Content (4 tools)\n\n| Tool | Description | Permission | Credit Cost |\n|------|-------------|------------|-------------|\n| `get_content_opportunities` | Returns signal-derived content opportunities with stakes scoring, play matching, persona targeting. | read | 0 |\n| `generate_content_angles` | Generates 2-4 content angles for a given opportunity. Returns angles with emotional framing and evidence summary. | draft | 1 |\n| `generate_linkedin_draft` | Generates a platform-specific draft from a content angle. Returns draft text, visual recommendation, and quality gate results. | draft | 2 |\n| `get_content_performance` | Returns performance metrics for published content: ICP engagement rate, warm lead rate, top plays. | read | 0 |\n\n**Maps to:** `endpoints/content/opportunities/list_GET`, `endpoints/content/angles/generate_POST`, `endpoints/content/drafts/generate_POST`, `endpoints/content/analytics/summary_GET`\n\n### Plays (3 tools)\n\n| Tool | Description | Permission | Credit Cost |\n|------|-------------|------------|-------------|\n| `recommend_play` | For a given account, returns matched GTME plays with confidence, urgency, trigger evidence, and matched contacts. | read | 0 |\n| `explain_play_fit` | For a specific play match, returns detailed breakdown: trigger certainty, action fit, evidence composition (direct vs inferred), suppression log, shadow state. | read | 0 |\n| `generate_play_action` | Given a play match, generates a recommended action plan: channels, message angles, timing, contacts to engage. No auto-execution. | draft | 1 |\n\n**Maps to:** `endpoints/gtme-plays/list_GET`, `endpoints/gtme-plays/detect_POST`, `helpers/gtmePlayDetector`\n\n### Follow-up (3 tools)\n\n| Tool | Description | Permission | Credit Cost |\n|------|-------------|------------|-------------|\n| `generate_outreach_draft` | Generates a personalized outreach message for a contact at an account. References actual signals and why-now context. Returns draft only — never sends. | draft | 1 |\n| `generate_public_reply` | Generates a suggested public reply to a social engagement event (e.g., X reply, LinkedIn comment). Interest-first, never pitchy. Returns draft only. | draft | 1 |\n| `prepare_crm_note` | Generates a structured CRM note for an account using crmNoteBuilder. Returns formatted note text — does not push to CRM. | draft | 0 |\n\n**Maps to:** `endpoints/ai/generate-message_POST`, `endpoints/social-monitor/leads/draft-outreach_POST`, `helpers/crmNoteBuilder`\n\n### Learning (4 tools)\n\n| Tool | Description | Permission | Credit Cost |\n|------|-------------|------------|-------------|\n| `get_signal_quality_summary` | Returns signal quality metrics: total signals, by family, avg confidence, false positive rate, source distribution. | read | 0 |\n| `get_false_positive_patterns` | Returns signals marked as false positives with pattern analysis: which sources, categories, and keywords produce the most noise. | read | 0 |\n| `get_source_quality_summary` | Returns per-source metrics: volume, review rate, false positive rate, mute status. From source trust system. | read | 0 |\n| `get_what_worked` | Returns signals that led to deals, enrollments, or CRM pushes. Attribution-based, not causation claims. | read | 0 |\n\n**Maps to:** `endpoints/analytics/signal-effectiveness_GET`, `endpoints/source-trust/metrics_GET`, `endpoints/gtme-plays/outcomes_GET`, `endpoints/analytics/attribution_GET`\n\n### Total: 26 tools (16 read, 7 draft, 3 write in v2)\n\n---\n\n## 4. Tool Response Design\n\nEvery MCP tool response follows a consistent structured format optimized for LLM reasoning:\n\n```typescript\ninterface McpToolResponse {\n  // Human-readable summary the LLM can use directly\n  summary: string;\n  \n  // Structured data payload (tool-specific)\n  data: Record<string, any>;\n  \n  // Evidence trail — source URLs, signal IDs, dates\n  evidence: Array<{\n    type: 'signal' | 'social_event' | 'job_posting' | 'news' | 'content';\n    id: string;\n    title: string;\n    sourceUrl?: string;\n    detectedAt: string;\n    confidence?: number;\n  }>;\n  \n  // Confidence in the response (0-100)\n  confidence: number;\n  \n  // Explicit caveats the LLM should communicate to the user\n  caveats: string[];\n  \n  // Suggested next action (tool name + suggested args)\n  recommendedNextAction?: {\n    tool: string;\n    description: string;\n    suggestedArgs: Record<string, any>;\n  };\n  \n  // IDs for follow-up tool calls\n  relatedIds: {\n    accountIds?: string[];\n    signalIds?: string[];\n    contactIds?: string[];\n    playIds?: string[];\n    draftIds?: string[];\n  };\n  \n  // Always present — confirms workspace scoping\n  workspace: {\n    id: string;\n    name: string;\n  };\n  \n  // Pagination when applicable\n  pagination?: {\n    total: number;\n    offset: number;\n    limit: number;\n    hasMore: boolean;\n  };\n}\n```\n\n**Design rules:**\n- Never return raw database rows. Always transform into the structured response format.\n- Never return bulk provider payloads (PDL, Exa, etc.). Only return SignalArk-processed intelligence.\n- Summaries must be written for LLM consumption — concise, factual, no marketing language.\n- Evidence arrays must include source URLs where available so the LLM can cite them.\n- Caveats must be honest: \"Based on 3 signals in the last 14 days\" not \"Comprehensive analysis.\"\n- Confidence scores must reflect data quality: low signal count = low confidence.\n- `recommendedNextAction` guides the LLM toward productive follow-up chains.\n- All responses capped at reasonable sizes (max 50 items per page, truncated summaries for large payloads).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Permissions and Safety Model\n\n### Tier 1: Read-only tools (16 tools)\n- Safe by default. No side effects.\n- All `search_*`, `get_*`, `explain_*` tools.\n- Return data the user already has access to in the UI.\n- Scoped to the user's workspace — no cross-workspace reads.\n\n### Tier 2: Drafting tools (7 tools)\n- Generate content but do NOT send, publish, or persist automatically.\n- All `generate_*` and `prepare_*` tools.\n- Responses contain draft text that the user must copy/paste/approve.\n- Credit-metered (1-2 credits per call via existing credit system).\n- Returned drafts include a caveat: \"This is a draft. Review before using.\"\n\n### Tier 3: Write tools (V2 only — 3+ tools)\n- Require explicit `mcp:write` scope on the API key.\n- Each write action logged to audit trail with full input/output.\n- V2 write tools:\n  - `save_signal_feedback` — mark signal as useful/false-positive\n  - `create_content_draft` — persist a generated draft to the content_drafts table\n  - `create_follow_up_task` — create an NBA/follow-up record\n  - `push_crm_note` — push a prepared note to HubSpot/Salesforce (with all existing eligibility gates)\n\n### Forbidden in V1 (and likely V2)\n- ❌ Send email (`outreach/send-email`)\n- ❌ Send DM (no endpoint exists, and it shouldn't)\n- ❌ Auto-enroll sequences (`outreach/enrollments/create`)\n- ❌ Mass-update CRM (`hubspot-sync`, `salesforce-sync`)\n- ❌ Call expensive external providers (PDL search, Exa, Apify) — these remain UI-only with explicit user confirmation\n- ❌ Expose cross-workspace data\n- ❌ Expose API keys, secrets, or admin-only data\n- ❌ Bulk account mutations (delete, merge, bulk-update)\n\n---\n\n## 6. Authentication\n\n### Mechanism: Workspace-scoped API key (Bearer token)\n\nSignalArk already has a robust API key system (`helpers/withApiKeyAuth`) with:\n- SHA-256 hashed key storage\n- Scope-based access control\n- Per-key rate limiting\n- Automatic `lastUsedAt` tracking\n- Workspace resolution via `teamMembers` join\n\n**MCP-specific additions:**\n\n1. **New scope: `mcp:read`** — grants access to all read-only MCP tools\n2. **New scope: `mcp:draft`** — grants access to drafting tools (credit-metered)\n3. **New scope: `mcp:write`** — grants access to write tools (V2)\n4. **MCP token generation UI** in Settings → Integrations → MCP Server:\n   - Generate MCP-specific API key with pre-selected `mcp:read` + `mcp:draft` scopes\n   - Copy-ready MCP client config (JSON for Claude Desktop, Cursor, etc.)\n   - One-click revocation\n   - Shows last used timestamp and call count\n\n**Authentication flow:**\n```\nClient → POST /mcp (Authorization: Bearer sak_xxxxx)\n  → withApiKeyAuth('mcp:read') validates token\n  → Resolves workspaceId + memberId\n  → Passes to MCP handler with workspace context\n```\n\n**Token format:** Same as existing API keys (`sak_` prefix, nanoid(32)).\n\n**Rate limiting:** Inherits per-key rate limit from `apiKeys.rateLimitPerMinute` (default 60/min). MCP-specific keys can have custom limits.\n\n**Audit:** Every MCP call logged to `audit_trail` via `rbacEngine.logAuditEvent`.\n\n**Session management:** Stateless. No MCP session IDs. Each request is independently authenticated via Bearer token. This is simpler and fits Floot's serverless model.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Audit and Logging\n\nEvery MCP tool invocation is logged to the existing `audit_trail` table:\n\n```typescript\n{\n  category: 'mcp',                    // New audit category\n  action: 'tools/call',               // Or 'tools/list', 'initialize'\n  actorId: memberId,                  // From API key resolution\n  entityType: 'mcp_tool',\n  entityId: toolName,                 // e.g. 'search_signals'\n  entityName: toolName,\n  metadata: {\n    tool: toolName,\n    inputSummary: truncatedInputArgs,  // First 500 chars of JSON args\n    outputSize: responseSizeBytes,\n    recordsAccessed: numberOfRecords,\n    creditsCost: creditsCost,\n    durationMs: executionTime,\n    clientId: clientIdentifier,        // From User-Agent or custom header\n    isWrite: false,\n  },\n  ipAddress: requestIp,\n  userAgent: userAgentHeader,\n}\n```\n\n**New DB table: `mcp_usage_logs`** (dedicated high-volume log for analytics, separate from audit_trail):\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE mcp_usage_logs (\n  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n  workspace_id TEXT NOT NULL REFERENCES workspaces(id),\n  member_id TEXT NOT NULL,\n  api_key_id TEXT NOT NULL,\n  tool_name TEXT NOT NULL,\n  input_hash TEXT,           -- SHA-256 of input for dedup analysis\n  output_size_bytes INT,\n  records_accessed INT,\n  credits_cost INT DEFAULT 0,\n  duration_ms INT,\n  status TEXT NOT NULL,      -- 'success', 'error', 'rate_limited', 'credit_exceeded'\n  error_message TEXT,\n  client_identifier TEXT,\n  created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW()\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX idx_mcp_usage_workspace ON mcp_usage_logs(workspace_id, created_at DESC);\nCREATE INDEX idx_mcp_usage_tool ON mcp_usage_logs(tool_name, created_at DESC);\n```\n\n**Queryable via:** Settings → Integrations → MCP Server → Usage Log (new UI tab).\n\n---\n\n## 8. Rate Limits and Cost Controls\n\n### Rate Limits\n\n| Category | Limit | Window | Enforcement |\n|----------|-------|--------|-------------|\n| Read tools | 60 calls/min per API key | 1 min sliding | `checkRateLimit` |\n| Draft tools (LLM-backed) | 20 calls/min per API key | 1 min sliding | `checkRateLimit` |\n| Write tools (V2) | 10 calls/min per API key | 1 min sliding | `checkRateLimit` |\n| Daily draft tool cap | 100 calls/day per workspace | 24h rolling | Custom counter |\n| `tools/list` | 10 calls/min per API key | 1 min sliding | Lightweight |\n\n### Credit Metering\n\nDraft tools consume credits via the existing `creditMeter` system:\n\n| Tool | Credits | Action Type |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `generate_content_angles` | 1 | `content_angle_gen` |\n| `generate_linkedin_draft` | 2 | `content_draft_gen` |\n| `generate_outreach_draft` | 1 | `ai_message_gen` |\n| `generate_public_reply` | 1 | `social_lead_outreach` |\n| `generate_play_action` | 1 | `ai_message_gen` |\n| `prepare_crm_note` | 0 | — |\n| All read tools | 0 | — |\n\nCredit checks happen before execution. If insufficient credits, the tool returns a structured error:\n```json\n{\n  \"isError\": true,\n  \"content\": [{\n    \"type\": \"text\",\n    \"text\": \"Credit limit exceeded. This tool requires 2 credits. You have 0 remaining this month. Visit Settings > Billing to purchase more.\"\n  }]\n}\n```\n\n### Cost Control Rules\n- No MCP tool triggers expensive external provider calls (PDL, Exa, Apify, Shodan, etc.)\n- Draft tools use the same LLM backends as the UI (Gemini 2.5 Flash primary, DeepSeek fallback)\n- No MCP tool can trigger batch operations (bulk scan, bulk enrichment, batch reclassify)\n- Rate limits are per-API-key, not per-workspace, so multiple team members don't interfere\n\n---\n\n## 9. V1 Scope — Smallest Useful MCP Server\n\n**Goal:** Ship the smallest MCP server that delivers real value for the \"plan my day from signals\" workflow.\n\n### V1 Tools (10 tools)\n\n**Read (8 tools):**\n1. `search_signals` — Search market radar signals with filters\n2. `get_signal_detail` — Full signal detail by ID\n3. `get_recent_high_priority_signals` — Top signals convenience wrapper\n4. `get_top_moving_accounts` — Accounts ranked by activity\n5. `get_account_timeline` — Unified account timeline\n6. `explain_account_priority` — Why this account matters\n7. `get_account_next_actions` — NBA for an account\n8. `get_content_opportunities` — Signal-derived content ideas\n\n**Draft (2 tools):**\n9. `generate_outreach_draft` — Draft an outreach message\n10. `generate_linkedin_draft` — Draft a LinkedIn post from a content opportunity\n\n**No write tools in V1.**\n\n### V1 Infrastructure\n- Single endpoint: `POST /_api/mcp` (Streamable HTTP transport)\n- `withApiKeyAuth` with `mcp:read` / `mcp:draft` scopes\n- JSON-RPC 2.0 message parsing\n- Tool registry with schema validation (Zod)\n- Structured response format\n- Audit logging to `audit_trail` + `mcp_usage_logs`\n- Rate limiting via existing `checkRateLimit`\n- Credit metering for draft tools\n- MCP token management UI in Settings → Integrations\n\n### V1 Excludes\n- No SSE streaming (all responses are request/response)\n- No MCP Resources or Prompts primitives (tools only)\n- No write tools\n- No social intelligence tools (added in V2)\n- No learning/analytics tools (added in V2)\n\n---\n\n## 10. V2 Scope — Social Intelligence + Controlled Writes\n\n### New Read Tools (8 tools)\n11. `get_social_activity` — Social engagement events\n12. `get_content_engagers` — Engagers on published content\n13. `get_competitor_social_mentions` — Competitor mentions in social\n14. `get_community_engagement_opportunities` — Warm non-lead engagement\n15. `get_signal_quality_summary` — Signal quality metrics\n16. `get_false_positive_patterns` — False positive analysis\n17. `get_source_quality_summary` — Source trust metrics\n18. `get_what_worked` — Signal-to-outcome attribution\n\n### New Draft Tools (2 tools)\n19. `generate_public_reply` — Draft social reply\n20. `prepare_crm_note` — Generate CRM note\n\n### New Write Tools (3 tools, require `mcp:write` scope)\n21. `save_signal_feedback` — Mark signal useful/false-positive\n22. `create_content_draft` — Persist generated draft\n23. `push_crm_note` — Push to HubSpot/Salesforce (with existing eligibility gates)\n\n### V2 Infrastructure Additions\n- `mcp:write` scope support\n- Write action confirmation protocol (return confirmation prompt, require re-call with `confirmed: true`)\n- MCP Resources primitive for ICP profile and company profile (read-only context)\n\n---\n\n## 11. V3 Scope — Compound Agent Workflows\n\n### MCP Prompts (pre-built workflow templates)\n- `plan_my_week` — Chains: recent signals → top accounts → plays → NBAs → formatted plan\n- `find_displacement_opportunities` — Chains: competitor signals → account timelines → outreach drafts\n- `create_content_from_signals` — Chains: content opportunities → angles → drafts\n- `prepare_account_outreach` — Chains: account detail → timeline → contacts → outreach drafts\n- `summarize_what_worked` — Chains: attribution → source quality → patterns\n\n### V3 Infrastructure\n- MCP Prompts primitive support\n- Prompt template registry\n- Multi-tool orchestration hints (suggested tool chains in responses)\n- SSE streaming for long-running compound workflows\n\n---\n\n## 12. Technical Implementation Plan\n\n### Endpoint Architecture\n\nSingle Floot endpoint handling all MCP traffic:\n\n```\nendpoints/mcp_POST\n```\n\nThis endpoint:\n1. Authenticates via `withApiKeyAuth` with `mcp:read` scope minimum\n2. Parses JSON-RPC 2.0 message\n3. Routes to method handler (`initialize`, `tools/list`, `tools/call`)\n4. Returns JSON-RPC 2.0 response\n\n**Why a single POST endpoint:**\n- Floot is serverless — no persistent connections\n- MCP Streamable HTTP transport uses POST for all client→server messages\n- No need for GET/SSE in V1 (no server-initiated notifications)\n- Stateless authentication per request fits serverless model perfectly\n\n### File Structure\n\n```\nhelpers/mcpServer.tsx              — MCP protocol handler (JSON-RPC parsing, routing, session)\nhelpers/mcpToolRegistry.tsx        — Tool definitions, schemas, descriptions\nhelpers/mcpToolHandlers.tsx        — Tool implementation functions (maps to existing endpoints/helpers)\nhelpers/mcpResponseFormatter.tsx   — Transforms internal data to McpToolResponse format\nhelpers/useMcpSettingsApi.tsx      — React Query hooks for MCP settings UI\nendpoints/mcp_POST.ts             — Single MCP endpoint\nendpoints/mcp_POST.schema.ts      — Schema (accepts any JSON-RPC body)\nendpoints/mcp/config_GET.ts       — Get MCP configuration for current workspace\nendpoints/mcp/usage_GET.ts        — Get MCP usage logs\n```\n\n### Tool Registry Design\n\n```typescript\n// helpers/mcpToolRegistry.tsx\ninterface McpToolDefinition {\n  name: string;\n  description: string;\n  inputSchema: ZodSchema;          // Zod schema (converted to JSON Schema for MCP)\n  permission: 'read' | 'draft' | 'write';\n  requiredScope: string;           // 'mcp:read', 'mcp:draft', 'mcp:write'\n  creditAction?: ActionType;       // If credit-metered\n  creditCost?: number;\n  rateLimitKey: string;            // For separate rate limit buckets\n  handler: (args: any, context: McpContext) => Promise<McpToolResponse>;\n}\n\nconst TOOL_REGISTRY: Record<string, McpToolDefinition> = {\n  search_signals: {\n    name: 'search_signals',\n    description: 'Search market radar signals by keyword, category, date range, confidence threshold. Returns paginated results sorted by intent score.',\n    inputSchema: z.object({\n      query: z.string().optional().describe('Free-text search query'),\n      category: z.enum(['high_intent', 'competitor_dissatisfaction', 'hiring_driven', 'funding_driven', 'ai_gtm_interest']).optional(),\n      daysBack: z.number().default(30).describe('How many days back to search'),\n      minConfidence: z.number().optional().describe('Minimum confidence score (0-100)'),\n      limit: z.number().default(20).describe('Max results to return'),\n      offset: z.number().default(0),\n    }),\n    permission: 'read',\n    requiredScope: 'mcp:read',\n    rateLimitKey: 'read',\n    handler: handleSearchSignals,\n  },\n  // ... more tools\n};\n```\n\n### JSON-RPC Flow\n\n```typescript\n// endpoints/mcp_POST.ts\nexport const handle = withApiKeyAuth('mcp:read', async (request, context) => {\n  const body = await request.json();\n  \n  // Validate JSON-RPC 2.0 envelope\n  if (body.jsonrpc !== '2.0') {\n    return jsonRpcError(body.id, -32600, 'Invalid Request');\n  }\n  \n  switch (body.method) {\n    case 'initialize':\n      return handleInitialize(body, context);\n    case 'tools/list':\n      return handleToolsList(body, context);\n    case 'tools/call':\n      return handleToolsCall(body, context);\n    case 'notifications/initialized':\n      // Client notification, no response needed\n      return new Response('', { status: 204 });\n    default:\n      return jsonRpcError(body.id, -32601, 'Method not found');\n  }\n});\n```\n\n### Mapping Tools to Existing Code\n\nTools call existing helpers/DB queries directly — they do NOT call other HTTP endpoints (which would cause access-denied errors in Floot's serverless model):\n\n| MCP Tool | Maps to |\n|----------|---------|\n| `search_signals` | Direct Kysely query on `market_radar_signals` using `marketRadarSignalCteHelpers` |\n| `get_signal_detail` | Direct Kysely query on `market_radar_signals` by ID |\n| `get_top_moving_accounts` | Direct Kysely query on `accounts` with signal count join |\n| `get_account_timeline` | Reuse logic from `endpoints/accounts/timeline_GET` (extract into helper) |\n| `explain_account_priority` | Direct Kysely queries on accounts + signals + plays + deals |\n| `get_account_next_actions` | Call `generateNextBestActions()` from `helpers/nextBestActionsEngine` |\n| `get_content_opportunities` | Direct Kysely query on `content_opportunities` |\n| `generate_outreach_draft` | Call `llmFallbackClient` with prompt from `helpers/promptTemplates` |\n| `generate_linkedin_draft` | Call `contentDraftGenerator` from existing content engine |\n\n**Important:** All queries are workspace-scoped using `context.workspaceId` from the API key resolution.\n\n### Response Format (No SuperJSON)\n\nMCP uses plain JSON-RPC, not SuperJSON. Tool responses are returned as `text` content type:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"jsonrpc\": \"2.0\",\n  \"id\": \"call-001\",\n  \"result\": {\n    \"content\": [\n      {\n        \"type\": \"text\",\n        \"text\": \"{\\\"summary\\\":\\\"Found 12 high-intent signals...\\\", \\\"data\\\": {...}, \\\"evidence\\\": [...]}\"\n      }\n    ],\n    \"isError\": false\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe `text` field contains the stringified `McpToolResponse` object. This is standard MCP — tool results are text content that the LLM reasons over.\n\n### Error Handling\n\n```typescript\n// Structured error responses\nfunction toolError(message: string, code?: string): McpToolResult {\n  return {\n    content: [{ type: 'text', text: JSON.stringify({\n      error: code || 'tool_error',\n      message,\n      caveats: [message],\n    })}],\n    isError: true,\n  };\n}\n\n// Error categories:\n// - auth_error: Invalid/expired API key\n// - scope_error: Missing required scope\n// - rate_limit: Rate limit exceeded\n// - credit_exceeded: Insufficient credits\n// - not_found: Signal/account not found\n// - validation_error: Invalid tool arguments\n// - internal_error: Unexpected server error\n```\n\n### Deployment Model\n\n- Deployed as regular Floot endpoints — no separate infrastructure\n- Stateless, serverless — each request is independent\n- No WebSocket, no persistent connections\n- Timeout: 3 minutes (Floot serverless limit) — sufficient for all V1 tools\n- No background jobs triggered by MCP (all responses are synchronous)\n\n---\n\n## 13. Data Access Rules\n\n1. **No cross-workspace leakage:** Every query filters by `workspace_id = context.workspaceId`. This is enforced at the tool handler level, not just the endpoint level.\n\n2. **No raw provider payloads:** Never return raw PDL, Exa, Apify, or other provider responses. Only return SignalArk-processed data.\n\n3. **No private secrets:** Never return API keys, OAuth tokens, webhook secrets, or any value from environment variables.\n\n4. **No hidden admin data:** Admin-only endpoints (ops health, classifier failures, source router bake-off) are not exposed through MCP.\n\n5. **No beta data unless enabled:** Tools respect feature flags and tier gating. If a workspace doesn't have `content_opportunities` access, the `get_content_opportunities` tool returns an upgrade prompt.\n\n6. **No unsupported LinkedIn overclaims:** Social tools include platform caveats: \"LinkedIn data is limited to comments (via LinkdAPI beta). X/Twitter includes replies, quotes, and reposts (via Xquik).\"\n\n7. **Workspace-scoped only:** There is no admin/superuser mode for MCP. Even admin users only see their workspace data.\n\n8. **No PII beyond what's already in the user's workspace:** Contacts, emails, and names are returned only for contacts the workspace has already created/imported.\n\n---\n\n## 14. UX / Setup\n\n### Settings → Integrations → MCP Server\n\n**Tab 1: Setup**\n- Toggle: \"Enable MCP Server\" (generates endpoint URL)\n- \"Generate MCP Token\" button → creates API key with `mcp:read` + `mcp:draft` scopes\n- Copy-ready config blocks for:\n  - **Claude Desktop** (`claude_desktop_config.json` format)\n  - **Cursor** (`mcp.json` format)\n  - **ChatGPT** (instructions for Developer Mode)\n  - **Generic** (raw endpoint URL + Bearer token)\n- Token list with revoke buttons\n- Token last-used timestamp\n\n**Example Claude Desktop config output:**\n```json\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"signalark\": {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.signalark.app/_api/mcp\",\n      \"headers\": {\n        \"Authorization\": \"Bearer sak_xxxxx\"\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Tab 2: Tools**\n- List of all available tools with descriptions\n- Permission tier badges (Read / Draft / Write)\n- Credit cost per tool\n- Toggle to enable/disable individual tools per token (V2)\n\n**Tab 3: Usage Log**\n- Filterable table of MCP usage from `mcp_usage_logs`\n- Columns: timestamp, tool, status, credits used, duration, client\n- Export to CSV\n\n**Tab 4: Audit**\n- Links to Security → Audit Trail filtered by `category=mcp`\n\n---\n\n## 15. Example Workflows\n\n### \"What accounts should I work today?\"\n```\nUser → \"What accounts should I focus on today?\"\n\nAI Client → tools/call: get_top_moving_accounts({ limit: 8, daysBack: 7 })\n  ← Returns 8 accounts with signal counts, ICP scores, active plays\n\nAI Client → tools/call: explain_account_priority({ accountId: \"abc-123\" })\n  ← Returns structured priority explanation for top account\n\nAI Client → tools/call: get_account_next_actions({ accountId: \"abc-123\" })\n  ← Returns 3 next best actions with reasoning\n\nAI Client synthesizes: \"Your top priority today is Acme Corp (ICP score 87, 5 signals this week including a VP Sales hire and funding round). I recommend: 1) Execute the Funding Expansion Blitz play, 2) Draft outreach to the new VP Sales, 3) Create a deal opportunity.\"\n```\n\n### \"Find competitor displacement signals this week\"\n```\nUser → \"Find competitor displacement signals this week\"\n\nAI Client → tools/call: search_signals({ category: \"competitor_dissatisfaction\", daysBack: 7, limit: 10 })\n  ← Returns 6 signals about competitor layoffs, pricing changes, support issues\n\nAI Client → tools/call: get_account_timeline({ accountId: \"def-456\" })\n  ← Shows the full signal history for the most affected account\n\nAI Client → tools/call: generate_outreach_draft({ accountId: \"def-456\", contactId: \"ghi-789\", context: \"competitor layoff signal\" })\n  ← Returns draft outreach referencing the competitor situation\n\nAI Client: \"I found 6 displacement opportunities this week. The strongest is TechCorp — their main competitor just announced 200 layoffs. Here's a draft outreach for their VP Engineering...\"\n```\n\n### \"Create 3 LinkedIn content ideas from recent hiring signals\"\n```\nUser → \"Create 3 LinkedIn post ideas from this week's hiring signals\"\n\nAI Client → tools/call: search_signals({ category: \"hiring_driven\", daysBack: 7, limit: 20 })\n  ← Returns 15 hiring signals\n\nAI Client → tools/call: get_content_opportunities({ limit: 5 })\n  ← Returns 3 content opportunities derived from hiring signals\n\nAI Client → tools/call: generate_content_angles({ opportunityId: \"opp-001\" })\n  ← Returns 3 angles with emotional framing\n\nAI Client → tools/call: generate_linkedin_draft({ angleId: \"ang-001\" })\n  ← Returns draft with visual recommendation\n\nAI Client: \"Here are 3 LinkedIn post ideas grounded in this week's hiring data: 1) 'AI companies are hiring 3x more sales engineers than SDRs — here's what that means for your outbound strategy...' [draft attached]\"\n```\n\n### \"Draft follow-up to ICP-fit engagers from our latest post\"\n```\nUser → \"Who engaged with our latest published content? Draft follow-ups for ICP-fit ones.\"\n\nAI Client → tools/call: get_content_engagers({ limit: 20, icpTierFilter: [\"ideal\", \"strong\"] })\n  ← Returns 4 ICP-fit engagers with warmth scores\n\nAI Client → tools/call: generate_outreach_draft({ contactContext: engager1, messageType: \"linkedin\" })\n  ← Returns interest-first draft referencing their specific engagement\n\nAI Client: \"4 ICP-fit people engaged with your post 'Why manual signal research costs you 3 deals/month'. Here's a draft LinkedIn message for Sarah Chen (VP Sales at DataFlow, warmth 82)...\"\n```\n\n### \"Summarize all activity for Acme Corp\"\n```\nUser → \"Summarize all activity for Acme Corp\"\n\nAI Client → tools/call: get_account_timeline({ accountId: \"abc-123\", daysBack: 90 })\n  ← Returns 23 timeline events across signals, social, market radar\n\nAI Client → tools/call: explain_account_priority({ accountId: \"abc-123\" })\n  ← Returns ICP fit, play matches, deal status\n\nAI Client: \"Acme Corp (ICP score 87, Growth tier): 23 events in 90 days. Key highlights: VP Sales hired 3 weeks ago, Series B funding 6 weeks ago, 3 job postings for sales engineers, engaged with your content twice on X. Active play: Funding Expansion Blitz (confidence 78%). No deal created yet — recommended action: create deal and draft outreach to new VP Sales.\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## 16. Risks and Mitigations\n\n| Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n|------|----------|------------|\n| **Client LLM hallucination** | High | Structured responses with explicit evidence arrays and caveats. The LLM has real data to cite, reducing hallucination. Include caveat in `initialize` response: \"Always cite evidence from tool responses. Do not invent data.\" |\n| **Data overexposure** | Medium | Tool responses are curated summaries, not raw DB dumps. PII is limited to data the workspace already has. No admin data exposed. |\n| **Cross-workspace leakage** | Critical | Every query scoped by `workspace_id` from API key. No tool accepts workspace_id as input — it's always from auth context. |\n| **Uncontrolled writes** | High | V1 has zero write tools. V2 writes require `mcp:write` scope + confirmation protocol + audit logging. |\n| **Rate limit abuse** | Medium | Per-key rate limits. Separate buckets for read vs draft. Daily cap on draft tools. Automatic lockout after sustained abuse. |\n| **Credit abuse** | Medium | Draft tools credit-metered via existing system. Credit check before execution. Clear error when exhausted. |\n| **Stale/beta data misuse** | Medium | Responses include `detectedAt` timestamps and data freshness caveats. Beta features gated by tier. |\n| **User trusting LLM too much** | Medium | Every draft tool response includes: \"This is a generated draft. Review before sending.\" Every attribution includes: \"Based on signal correlation, not proven causation.\" |\n| **Token theft** | High | Tokens are workspace-scoped (blast radius limited). Revocation UI prominent. `lastUsedAt` tracking enables anomaly detection. Short expiry option available. |\n| **LLM prompt injection via signal data** | Medium | Tool responses are structured JSON, not raw text injected into prompts. Signal titles/summaries are sanitized. No user-supplied HTML in responses. |\n\n---\n\n## 17. Success Metrics\n\n### Activation\n- MCP tokens generated (per workspace, per week)\n- MCP config copied (track via UI event)\n- First successful `tools/call` within 24h of token creation\n\n### Engagement\n- Weekly active MCP users (≥1 tool call in 7 days)\n- Tool calls per user per week (target: 20+)\n- Session depth (avg tools called per \"conversation\")\n- Top tools by usage volume\n\n### Value\n- Account prioritization queries / week\n- Content drafts generated via MCP / week\n- Outreach drafts generated via MCP / week\n- Time from MCP draft → user action (e.g., deal created, email sent manually)\n\n### Quality\n- Error rate per tool (target: <2%)\n- Avg response time per tool (target: <3s for reads, <10s for drafts)\n- Credit consumption via MCP vs UI\n- False positive rate from MCP-surfaced signals\n\n### Safety\n- Unauthorized access attempts (should be 0)\n- Cross-workspace access attempts (should be 0)\n- Write tool usage patterns (monitor for abuse)\n- Token revocation rate (high = UX/trust issue)\n\n### Support\n- MCP-related support tickets\n- Setup success rate (generated token → successful call)\n\n---\n\n## 18. Final Recommendation\n\n### Build: **Internal beta first, then V1 after launch stabilization.**\n\n**Reasoning:**\n\n1. **Not now.** SignalArk is pre-launch with active users onboarding. The market pipeline was literally broken yesterday. Shipping MCP before the core product is rock-solid would be premature.\n\n2. **Not never.** MCP is the right bet. It's becoming the standard protocol for AI tool access. Claude, ChatGPT, and Cursor all support it. Being the first GTM signal platform with MCP access is a genuine differentiator.\n\n3. **Internal beta first (2-4 weeks post-launch stabilization):**\n   - Build V1 (10 tools, read + draft) as an internal/design-partner feature\n   - Dog-food with the SignalArk team and 2-3 design partners\n   - Validate the tool response format actually helps LLMs reason well\n   - Identify which tools get used vs. ignored\n   - Tune rate limits and credit costs based on real usage\n\n4. **Public V1 (4-6 weeks after internal beta):**\n   - Ship with Settings → Integrations → MCP Server UI\n   - Gate behind `pro` tier (API keys are already pro-tier gated)\n   - Announce as \"SignalArk for Claude / ChatGPT / Cursor\"\n   - Measure activation and engagement\n\n5. **V2 (8-12 weeks af